         <abstract id="aspace_1abf5585b8ee213f34f808823b9c4115">Published articles and manuscript maps created by John Neilson Barry, circa 1912-1944. Articles have been handbound by Barry and include his manuscript and typescript annotations as well as his illustrated maps of Oregon, Washington, and Idaho. Materials pertain to the histories of Oregon and Washington with a focus on expeditions through the Pacific Northwest and along the Columbia River, specifically the Astor Expedition (1810-1813), Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804-1806), and John Colter's explorations (1807-1808).</abstract>
    
      </did>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_c0f11144270d8cee5b61a36e8085a668">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>This collection is open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_350ed720c3612bd2438668dc97b25ea4">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of J. Neilson Barry, 1942-1943. Transferred from Sterling Memorial Library, Yale University, 2016.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <arrangement id="aspace_7d12c4ea5e3217e62741743ece0e0fab">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Arranged alphabetically by title assigned by J. Neilson Barry to bound works.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <bioghist id="aspace_5c7b4c69c5652f7780370e931562ebef">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>John Neilson Barry (1870-1961) of Wilmington, North Carolina, served as an Episcopal minister in Spokane, Washington; New York, New York; Washington, District of Columbia; and Baker, Oregon, from 1895 to 1913. From 1913 to 1922, Barry served as a probation officer with the police court in Spokane. He retired in 1922 and moved to Portland, Oregon, where he conducted historical research, focusing on maps of the Pacific Northwest and showing interest in John Colter, a member of the Lewis and Clark Expedition.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_7e62d74407ba7e64cbd1484d50c48ae8">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>J. Neilson Barry Collection of Western Maps. Yale Collection of Western Americana, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <processinfo id="aspace_d79d3dc778fddcf76fbf2f1811a4f5e7">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.</p>
         <p>These materials have been arranged and described according to national and local standards. For more information, please refer to the Beinecke Manuscript Unit Processing Manual.</p>
         <p>Folders have been titled according to original titles given by J. Neilson Barry to individual maps and published articles. Supplied folder titles are bracketed.</p>  
      </processinfo>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_816fe155d05f29f7063f29aa2509f0b5">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Published articles and manuscript maps created by John Neilson Barry, circa 1912-1944. Articles have been handbound by Barry and include manuscript and typescript annotations as well as illustrated maps of Oregon, Washington, and Idaho. Materials pertain to the histories of Oregon and Washington with a focus on expeditions through the Pacific Northwest and along the Columbia River, specifically the Astor Expedition (1810-1813), Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804-1806), and John Colter's explorations (1807-1808). Correspondence in the collection is from Barry to Sterling Memorial Library staff, providing supplementary information to his bound works.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_6bbcaf999307b312cde5f9e6c06d3fb4">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The J. Neilson Barry Collection of Western Maps is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.</p>  
      </userestrict>
